{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-860d04c9ede49288", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tTokenizer Transplantation: Mitigating Autoregressive Collapse in Edge-Efficient\n2\tBengali ASR\n3\t\n4\tSanjid Hasan 1 Md. Abdur Rahman 2\n5\t\n6\tarXiv:2607.09598v1 [cs.CL] 10 Jul 2026\n7\t\n8\tAbstract\n9\t\n10\tIn this paper, we address this bottleneck by proposing a\n11\tTokenizer Transplantation pipeline. Rather than training\n12\tfrom scratch, we surgically adapt a lightweight base architecture (e.g., Moonshine) by replacing its vocabulary with\n13\ta native-script BanglaBERT tokenizer. We show that by\n14\tdecoupling acoustic representation learning from language\n15\tmodeling, we can stabilize the decoder and significantly improve performance on the 882-hour Lipi-Ghor dataset. Our\n16\tapproach provides a scalable blueprint for adapting efficient,\n17\tpre-trained architectures to under-represented languages,\n18\tensuring that the benefits of ASR reach linguistically diverse communities. The full implementation details for our\n19\tframework are available in our repository.1\n20\t\n21\tLightweight speech recognition models are critical for edge deployment, yet highly optimized\n22\tarchitectures like Moonshine often fail on morphologically rich, non-Latin languages such as\n23\tBengali. This study identifies the root cause of\n24\tthis failure as the model’s English-centric bytelevel tokenizer, which fragments Bengali words\n25\tinto high-fertility byte chains and triggers catastrophic autoregressive collapse during inference.\n26\tTo resolve this, a novel vocabulary transplantation\n27\tpipeline is proposed to replace the decoder vocabulary with the native-script BanglaBERT WordPiece vocabulary and resize the corresponding\n28\ttoken embedding matrix. Experimental results\n29\tdemonstrate a reduction in token fertility from\n30\t9.16 to 1.30. By decreasing autoregressive sequence length by 85.8%, decoding instability is\n31\tentirely mitigated. When evaluated on the 882hour Lipi-Ghor dataset, the modified architecture\n32\tachieves a competitive 21.54% Word Error Rate\n33\t(WER) and a Real-Time Factor (RTF) of 0.0053.\n34\tUltimately, this research provides a scalable, reproducible blueprint for cross-script adaptation\n35\tof compact ASR models without the need for\n36\tresource-intensive pre-training.\n37\t\n38\t2. Related Work\n39\t2.1. Speech Representation Learning\n40\tThe current ASR landscape is dominated by frameworks\n41\tsuch as Baevski et al. (2020) and Babu et al. (2022), which\n42\tleverage self-supervised learning for robust feature extraction. While models like Radford et al. (2023) have pushed\n43\tthe boundaries of accuracy via large-scale supervision, their\n44\tcomputational footprint remains prohibitive for edge devices. Consequently, lightweight architectures like Moonshine (Useful Sensors, 2024; King & Sabra, 2025) have\n45\temerged as essential for local, resource-constrained deployment.\n46\t\n47\t1. Introduction\n48\t\n49\t2.2. Vocabulary Adaptation\n50\t\n51\tRecent advancements in Automatic Speech Recognition\n52\t(ASR) have achieved remarkable performance through largescale, self-supervised learning. However, these models often rely on broad-coverage tokenizers designed for highresource languages, which perform suboptimally on morphologically rich languages like Bengali. This mismatch\n53\tresults in high token fertility, leading to increased sequence\n54\tlength and autoregressive collapse during inference.\n55\t\n56\tTokenization quality is a primary determinant of model\n57\tperformance (Rust et al., 2021). Prior efforts, such as\n58\tWECHSEL (Minixhofer et al., 2022) and FOCUS (Dobler &\n59\tde Melo, 2023), have proposed innovative ways to initialize\n60\tsubword embeddings for cross-lingual transfer. However,\n61\tthese methods primarily address text-based Large Language\n62\tModels (LLMs). Our work extends these principles to ASR\n63\tby identifying ”tokenizer transplantation” as a critical requirement for preventing autoregressive drift in morphologically rich scripts.\n64\t\n65\t1\n66\t\n67\tKhulna University of Engineering & Technology, Bangladesh\n68\tMilitary Institute of Science and Technology, Bangladesh. Correspondence to: Sanjid Hasan <hasan2203090@stud.kuet.ac.bd>.\n69\t2\n70\t\n71\t1\n72\thttps://github.com/Sanjidh090/moonshin\n73\te-base-bn\n74\t\n75\tProceedings of the 43 rd International Conference on Machine\n76\tLearning, Seoul, South Korea. PMLR 306, 2026. Copyright 2026\n77\tby the author(s).\n78\t\n79\t1\n80\t\n81\t\fTokenizer Transplantation for Bengali ASR\n82\t\n83\t2.3. Bengali ASR\n84\t\n85\tthe network our pipeline begins by fine-tuning the vanilla\n86\tMoonshine-Base model on the Bengali dataset for 21 epochs.\n87\tThis allows the encoder to adapt its acoustic representations\n88\tto Bengali phonetics. However, while the training loss converges, the decoder fails to produce coherent text due to the\n89\textreme sequence lengths generated by the native Englishoptimized tokenizer.\n90\t\n91\tThe development of Bengali ASR has been accelerated by\n92\tdatasets like Alam et al. (2022) and Faisal et al. (2023).\n93\tWhile recent works (Tabib et al., 2026) have explored longform ASR and speaker diarization (Bredin et al., 2020),\n94\tthere remains a gap in adapting state-of-the-art decoders\n95\tto these languages. By integrating techniques such as\n96\tTokAlign (Liu et al., 2025) and Trans-Tokenization (Delobelle et al., 2024), we provide a robust, reproducible methodology for language-specific vocabulary adaptation.\n97\t\n98\t4.2. Phase 2: Tokenizer Transplantation\n99\tTo resolve the decoding bottleneck while retaining the newly\n100\tlearned acoustic weights, tokenizer transplantation is performed on the 21-epoch fine-tuned model. The original\n101\tdecoder tokenizer is replaced with the BUET BanglaBERT\n102\tWordPiece tokenizer (Bhattacharjee et al., 2022). Decoder\n103\tembeddings are mathematically resized from the original vocabulary size (Vold ) to the Bengali target vocabulary (Vnew ).\n104\t\n105\t3. Tokenizer Fertility and Decoding Instability\n106\tThe original Moonshine tokenizer was optimized primarily for English text. As a result, Bengali words undergo\n107\taggressive byte-level decomposition during tokenization.\n108\tTokenizer fertility is defined as the ratio of generated tokens\n109\tto the total number of words:\n110\t\n111\tΦ=\n112\t\n113\tTotal Tokens\n114\tTotal Words\n115\t\n116\tSpecial tokens are remapped explicitly to preserve decoder\n117\tcompatibility (e.g., mapping BanglaBERT’s ⟨CLS⟩ →\n118\tBOS and ⟨SEP ⟩ → EOS). The 61.5M parameter encoder\n119\tarchitecture remains unchanged, preserving the Bengaliadapted acoustic representations learned during Phase 1.\n120\t\n121\t(1)\n122\t\n123\twhere lower values indicate more compact tokenization. The baseline tokenizer produces Φbaseline = 9.16.\n124\tIn contrast, the transplanted Bengali tokenizer achieves\n125\tΦtransplant = 1.30.\n126\t\n127\t4.3. Phase 3: Two-Stage Recovery Optimization\n128\tBecause the new decoder embeddings are randomly initialized while the acoustic encoder is already fine-tuned,\n129\tstandard optimization leads to transplant rejection and catastrophic forgetting. To stabilize decoder adaptation, a twostage recovery fine-tuning approach is utilized, as illustrated\n130\tin Figure 1:\n131\t\n132\tThe fertility gap substantially affects autoregressive decoding. Long token chains increase the probability of inferencetime error accumulation (Sennrich et al., 2016). Although\n133\tteacher-forced optimization remains stable, autoregressive\n134\tgeneration becomes increasingly fragile, explaining the observed discrepancy between training loss and inference quality.\n135\t\n136\tStage 1 (High LR Recovery): An aggressive initial learning rate (η = 2 × 10−4 ) is applied using the ScheduleFree\n137\tAdamW optimizer (Defazio et al., 2024). This rapidly aligns\n138\tthe new textual embeddings to the acoustic latent space over\n139\t7 epochs without degrading the robust encoder weights.\n140\t\n141\t4. Methodology\n142\t\n143\tStage 2 (Stabilization): Training is resumed from the\n144\t7-epoch checkpoint with a heavily decayed learning rate\n145\t(η = 2 × 10−5 ) to fine-tune the model for grammatical and\n146\tphonetic accuracy.\n147\t\n148\tTo address the catastrophic decoding drift caused by high\n149\ttokenizer fertility, a novel three-phase adaptation pipeline is\n150\tproposed. Rather than training a model from scratch or replacing the vocabulary before fine-tuning, which often leads\n151\tto catastrophic forgetting, the approach explicitly decouples acoustic representation learning from autoregressive\n152\tlanguage modeling. In this section, the sequential steps of\n153\tthe framework are detailed: initial acoustic adaptation of the\n154\tbase model, surgical transplantation of a native-script vocabulary, and a specialized recovery optimization schedule\n155\tdesigned to stabilize the newly initialized decoder embeddings.\n156\t\n157\tTo maximize memory efficiency, BF16 Automatic Mixed\n158\tPrecision (AMP), gradient checkpointing, and gradient accumulation (step 8) are applied to achieve an effective batch\n159\tsize of 32 throughout both stages.\n160\t\n161\t5. Experimental Setup\n162\tAll model adaptations and recovery fine-tuning schedules were implemented using PyTorch, leveraging a local\n163\tNVIDIA GeForce RTX 4070 hardware accelerator with\n164\t12.9 GB VRAM to support memory-efficient execution via\n165\tAutomatic Mixed Precision (AMP) and gradient checkpointing. Transcript evaluations, Word Error Rate (WER) met-\n166\t\n167\t4.1. Phase 1: Initial Acoustic Fine-Tuning\n168\tRather than replacing the tokenizer prior to any training\n169\twhich often destroys pretrained alignments and destabilizes\n170\t2\n171\t\n172\t\fTokenizer Transplantation for Bengali ASR\n173\tPhase 1: Acoustic Adaptation & Surgery\n174\t\n175\tPhase 2: Two-Stage Transplant Recovery\n176\t\n177\tTransplanted\n178\tModel\n179\t\n180\t1. Initial Acoustic Fine-Tuning\n181\t\n182\t3. Stage 1: High LR Recovery\n183\t\n184\t• Model: Moonshine-Base (61.5M)\n185\t\n186\t• Base: Transplanted Architecture\n187\t\n188\t• Optim: AdamW (η = 2 × 10−5 )\n189\t\n190\t• Optim: ScheduleFree AdamW (η = 2 × 10−4 )\n191\t\n192\t• Result: 21-Epoch Adapted Encoder\n193\t\n194\t• Result: 7-Epoch Checkpoint\n195\t\n196\tExtract\n197\t21-Ep Encoder\n198\t\n199\t7-Epoch\n200\tCheckpoint\n201\t\n202\tPhase 3: Validation Pipeline\n203\t\n204\t5. Autoregressive Evaluation\n205\t\n206\tEpoch-Level\n207\tEval\n208\t\n209\t• Gen: Beam Search (Width=4, Pen=1.2)\n210\t• Metric: Greedy WER (Random 64 Subset)\n211\t• Target: Save on Best WER (Patience=4)\n212\t\n213\t2. Tokenizer Transplantation\n214\t\n215\t4. Stage 2: Stabilization\n216\t\n217\t• Base: 21-Ep Fine-Tuned Encoder\n218\t\n219\t• Base: 7-Epoch Transplant Checkpoint\n220\t\n221\t• Swap: BanglaBERT Vocabulary Transplant\n222\t\n223\t• Optim: Reduced LR (η = 2 × 10−5 )\n224\t\n225\t• Align: Map ⟨CLS⟩ → BOS, ⟨SEP ⟩ → EOS\n226\t\n227\t• Updates: Dynamic Masking Enabled\n228\t\n229\tFigure 1. Overview of the Tokenizer Transplantation Methodology.\n230\t\n231\tric verification computations, and Real-Time Factor (RTF)\n232\tspeed benchmarking profiles were executed using the cloudhosted Kaggle environment.\n233\t\n234\tdrift observed in the baseline.\n235\t\n236\tTable 1. Tokenizer Fertility Comparison\n237\t\n238\t5.1. Dataset\n239\t\n240\tTokenizer\n241\t\n242\tExperiments utilize the Lipi-Ghor-882 dataset (Hasan et al.,\n243\t2026), an 882-hour multi-speaker Bengali corpus curated\n244\tfrom diverse open-source media. Audio is normalized to\n245\t16kHz mono. Silent segments and non-speech artifacts are\n246\taggressively filtered using Voice Activity Detection (VAD)\n247\tvia Pyannote (Bredin et al., 2020). This builds upon foundational Bengali speech corpora such as OOD-Speech (Faisal\n248\tet al., 2023) and Bengali Common Voice (Alam et al., 2022)\n249\tby offering long-form, highly diverse multi-speaker data.\n250\t\n251\tOriginal Moonshine\n252\tTransplanted Bengali (BUET)\n253\t\n254\tFertility (Φ)\n255\t9.16\n256\t1.30\n257\t\n258\t6.2. End-to-End ASR Performance\n259\tTo evaluate the real-world efficacy of the tokenizer transplantation pipeline, the proposed model is compared against\n260\ta spectrum of zero-shot and fine-tuned baselines on the 5%\n261\theld-out Lipi-Ghor test set (comprising 5,931 utterances).\n262\t\n263\t5.2. Evaluation Metrics\n264\tTranscription quality is evaluated using Word Error Rate\n265\t(WER) and Character Error Rate (CER), while inference\n266\tefficiency is measured using Real-Time Factor (RTF). During training, Greedy WER is monitored on a randomized\n267\t64-sample validation subset at the end of each epoch, utilizing beam search (width = 4, repetition penalty = 1.2).\n268\tEarly stopping is triggered based on the best WER, with a\n269\tpatience of four epochs.\n270\t\n271\tAs detailed in Table 2, the transplanted Moonshine-Base\n272\tarchitecture achieves a highly competitive Word Error Rate\n273\t(WER) of 21.54%, substantially outperforming both the\n274\tZero-Shot Meta MMS 1B and the Fine-Tuned Conformer\n275\tbaselines.\n276\tMost notably, the proposed model achieves a Character\n277\tError Rate (CER) of 10.79%, the lowest among all tested\n278\tarchitectures. This indicates that the native-script vocabulary empowers the decoder to construct morphologically\n279\tcomplex Bengali words with higher sub-word accuracy than\n280\tthe byte-fallback approach utilized by Whisper. Furthermore, this accuracy is achieved with an order-of-magnitude\n281\treduction in parameters, matching the performance of the\n282\t∼769M parameter Faster Whisper Medium model with only\n283\t∼61.5M parameters.\n284\t\n285\t6. Results\n286\t6.1. Mitigation of Autoregressive Collapse\n287\tTokenizer transplantation dramatically reduces Bengali sequence fragmentation (Table 1). By compressing the token\n288\trepresentations, autoregressive decoding becomes substantially more stable, completely preventing the catastrophic\n289\t\n290\t3\n291\t\n292\t\fTokenizer Transplantation for Bengali ASR\n293\tTable 2. Global ASR Performance Comparison on the Lipi-Ghor Test Set. The proposed transplanted Moonshine model achieves a\n294\tcompetitive WER and the lowest CER while operating with significantly fewer parameters than the Whisper and Conformer baselines.\n295\t\n296\tPre-training Strategy\n297\t\n298\tModel Architecture\n299\t\n300\tParameters\n301\t\n302\tWER (%)\n303\t\n304\tCER (%)\n305\t\n306\tZero-Shot\n307\tZero-Shot\n308\tZero-Shot\n309\tZero-Shot\n310\t\n311\tSeamless M4T-v2\n312\tOpenAI Whisper large-v3\n313\tMeta MMS 1B\n314\tHishab TITU Conformer Large\n315\t\n316\t∼2.3B\n317\t∼1.55B\n318\t∼1B\n319\t∼120M\n320\t\n321\t66.71\n322\t84.53\n323\t43.06\n324\t30.51\n325\t\n326\t45.54\n327\t72.92\n328\t21.16\n329\t18.23\n330\t\n331\tFine-Tuned\n332\tFine-Tuned\n333\t\n334\tConformer Baseline (fast-conformer)\n335\tFaster Whisper Medium (Tustugi)\n336\t\n337\t∼120M\n338\t∼769M\n339\t\n340\t24.67\n341\t21.28\n342\t\n343\t15.56\n344\t11.18\n345\t\n346\tProposed\n347\t\n348\tMoonshine Base (Transplanted Tokenizer)\n349\t\n350\t∼61.5M\n351\t\n352\t21.54\n353\t\n354\t10.79\n355\t\n356\tTable 3. Inference Efficiency on the 22-Hour DL Sprint Benchmark. The proposed model drastically outperforms competition\n357\tbaselines in speed while recovering accuracy.\n358\tModel Architecture\n359\t\n360\tOptimization\n361\t\n362\tTime (22h)\n363\t\n364\tRTF\n365\t\n366\tWhisper-Medium\n367\tHishab-Titu Conformer\n368\tProposed Moonshine-base\n369\tMoonshine-tiny\n370\t\n371\tCTranslate2 / Dual T4\n372\tStandard PyTorch\n373\tTokenizer Transplant\n374\tBaseline (Failed WER)\n375\t\n376\t∼26 min\n377\t∼17 min\n378\t∼7 min\n379\t∼5 min\n380\t\n381\t0.0190\n382\t0.0120\n383\t0.0053\n384\t0.0038\n385\t\n386\t7. Conclusion\n387\tThis study introduced tokenizer transplantation for the Bengali adaptation of the Moonshine ASR model. Analysis\n388\tidentified excessive tokenizer fertility as a primary source\n389\tof autoregressive instability in compact models. By initially fine-tuning the acoustic representations, replacing the\n390\tnative tokenizer with a morphologically aligned Bengali\n391\ttokenizer, and implementing a two-stage recovery training\n392\tpipeline, inference stability on the Lipi-Ghor dataset was\n393\tsubstantially improved. These findings demonstrate that\n394\tdecoupling acoustic adaptation from vocabulary alignment\n395\tserves as a critical, underexplored strategy for democratizing lightweight ASR systems in low-resource languages.\n396\t\n397\tFigure 2. Efficiency Frontier. The proposed model (cyan)\n398\tachieves a favorable trade-off between performance and efficiency.\n399\t\n400\t6.3. Inference Efficiency and Edge Viability\n401\tTo contextualize the computational efficiency of the proposed architecture, inference speeds were compared against\n402\ttop-performing baselines evaluated during the DL Sprint 4.0\n403\tBengali ASR competition (Hasan et al., 2026). Benchmarks\n404\tare calculated based on the 22-hour hidden test set utilized\n405\tin the competition.\n406\t\n407\tAcknowledgments\n408\t\n409\tAs demonstrated in Table 3, while standard architectures like\n410\tWhisper-Medium required heavily engineered, parallelized\n411\tCTranslate2 pipelines (Klein et al., 2017) to achieve a RealTime Factor (RTF) of ∼0.019, the proposed MoonshineBase with the transplanted BanglaBERT tokenizer achieves\n412\tan RTF of 0.0053 natively.\n413\t\n414\tThe authors express their sincere gratitude to the Department\n415\tof Computer Science and Engineering (CSE) at Khulna University of Engineering & Technology (KUET) for providing\n416\taccess to the specialized PC environment used to execute\n417\tthe fine-tuning and core adaptation stages of this research.\n418\t\n419\tAlthough the original vanilla Moonshine model processes\n420\tthe 22-hour set in slightly less time (RTF ∼0.0038), it yields\n421\tcatastrophic WERs near 100% (Hasan et al., 2026). Tokenizer transplantation slightly increases sequence processing\n422\ttime due to accurate autoregressive generation, yet successfully salvages the model’s accuracy while remaining 3.5×\n423\tfaster than highly optimized Whisper deployments and 2.2×\n424\tfaster than Conformer architectures.\n425\t\n426\tReferences\n427\tAlam, S. et al. Bengali common voice speech dataset for\n428\tautomatic speech recognition. ResearchGate, 2022.\n429\tBabu, A., Wang, C., Tjandra, A., et al. Xls-r: Selfsupervised cross-lingual speech representation learning\n430\tat scale. In Proceedings of Interspeech, 2022.\n431\t4\n432\t\n433\t\fTokenizer Transplantation for Bengali ASR\n434\t\n435\tBaevski, A., Zhou, H., Mohamed, A., and Auli, M. wav2vec\n436\t2.0: A framework for self-supervised learning of speech\n437\trepresentations. In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2020.\n438\t\n439\tRust, P., Pfeiffer, J., Vulić, I., Litschko, S., and Glavaš, G.\n440\tHow good is your tokenizer? on the monolingual performance of multilingual language models. In Proceedings\n441\tof the Association for Computational Linguistics (ACL),\n442\t2021.\n443\t\n444\tBhattacharjee, A., Hasan, M. T., Ahmad, W., et al.\n445\tBanglabert: Language model pretraining and evaluating\n446\tunder-resourced language nlp. In Findings of the Association for Computational Linguistics: EMNLP, 2022.\n447\t\n448\tSennrich, R., Haddow, B., and Birch, A. Neural machine\n449\ttranslation of rare words with subword units. In Proceedings of the Association for Computational Linguistics\n450\t(ACL), 2016.\n451\t\n452\tBredin, H., Yin, R., Coria, J. M., et al. pyannote.audio: neural building blocks for speaker diarization. In Proceedings of the IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\n453\tSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2020.\n454\t\n455\tTabib, H. M. S., Rifti, I. A., Ehsan, A. M. A., Dasgupta,\n456\tS., Sowdha, M. Z. M. S., Sarker, A. J., Hasan, M. M.,\n457\tSaha, A., Nobo, M. N. M., Bhattacharjee, S., Bhomik,\n458\tT., Swapnil, A. N., and Kabir, S. Bengali-loop: Community benchmarks for long-form bangla asr and speaker\n459\tdiarization, 2026.\n460\t\n461\tDefazio, A., Mishchenko, K., and Bottou, L. The road\n462\tless scheduled. In Proceedings of the 41st International\n463\tConference on Machine Learning (ICML), 2024.\n464\t\n465\tUseful Sensors. Moonshine: Lightweight speech recognition models. GitHub repository, 2024.\n466\t\n467\tDelobelle, P. et al. Trans-tokenization and cross-lingual vocabulary transfers: Language adaptation of llms for lowresource nlp. arXiv preprint arXiv:2408.04303, 2024.\n468\tDobler, K. and de Melo, G. Focus: Effective embedding\n469\tinitialization for monolingual specialization of multilingual models. In Proceedings of the Empirical Methods in\n470\tNatural Language Processing (EMNLP), 2023.\n471\tFaisal, F. et al. Ood-speech: A large bengali speech recognition dataset for out-of-distribution benchmarking. arXiv\n472\tpreprint arXiv:2305.09688, 2023.\n473\tHasan, S. et al. Make it hard to hear, easy to learn: Longform bengali asr and speaker diarization. arXiv preprint\n474\tarXiv:2602.23070, 2026.\n475\tKing, J. and Sabra, A. Flavors of moonshine: Tiny specialized asr models for edge devices. arXiv preprint\n476\tarXiv:2509.02523, 2025.\n477\tKlein, G., Kim, Y., Deng, Y., Senellart, J., and Rush, A. M.\n478\tOpennmt: Open-source toolkit for neural machine translation, 2017.\n479\tLiu, Y. et al. Tokalign: Efficient vocabulary adaptation via\n480\ttoken alignment. In Proceedings of the Association for\n481\tComputational Linguistics (ACL), 2025.\n482\tMinixhofer, B. et al. Wechsel: Effective initialization of\n483\tsubword embeddings for cross-lingual transfer of monolingual language models. In Proceedings of the North\n484\tAmerican Chapter of the Association for Computational\n485\tLinguistics (NAACL), 2022.\n486\tRadford, A., Kim, J. W., Xu, T., et al. Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision. In Proceedings\n487\tof the International Conference on Machine Learning\n488\t(ICML), 2023.\n489\t5\n490\t\n491\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "d0639bc2-0cc8-4840-ad5d-84756428afec", "uuid": "17cfec20-acc4-43c8-aaf5-8dc7a480d150", "timestamp": "2026-07-13T07:04:18.457Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.09598.txt", "content": "Tokenizer Transplantation: Mitigating Autoregressive Collapse in Edge-Efficient\nBengali ASR\n\nSanjid Hasan 1 Md. Abdur Rahman 2\n\narXiv:2607.09598v1 [cs.CL] 10 Jul 2026\n\nAbstract\n\nIn this paper, we address this bottleneck by proposing a\nTokenizer Transplantation pipeline. Rather than training\nfrom scratch, we surgically adapt a lightweight base architecture (e.g., Moonshine) by replacing its vocabulary with\na native-script BanglaBERT tokenizer. We show that by\ndecoupling acoustic representation learning from language\nmodeling, we can stabilize the decoder and significantly improve performance on the 882-hour Lipi-Ghor dataset. Our\napproach provides a scalable blueprint for adapting efficient,\npre-trained architectures to under-represented languages,\nensuring that the benefits of ASR reach linguistically diverse communities. The full implementation details for our\nframework are available in our repository.1\n\nLightweight speech recognition models are critical for edge deployment, yet highly optimized\narchitectures like Moonshine often fail on morphologically rich, non-Latin languages such as\nBengali. This study identifies the root cause of\nthis failure as the model’s English-centric bytelevel tokenizer, which fragments Bengali words\ninto high-fertility byte chains and triggers catastrophic autoregressive collapse during inference.\nTo resolve this, a novel vocabulary transplantation\npipeline is proposed to replace the decoder vocabulary with the native-script BanglaBERT WordPiece vocabulary and resize the corresponding\ntoken embedding matrix. Experimental results\ndemonstrate a reduction in token fertility from\n9.16 to 1.30. By decreasing autoregressive sequence length by 85.8%, decoding instability is\nentirely mitigated. When evaluated on the 882hour Lipi-Ghor dataset, the modified architecture\nachieves a competitive 21.54% Word Error Rate\n(WER) and a Real-Time Factor (RTF) of 0.0053.\nUltimately, this research provides a scalable, reproducible blueprint for cross-script adaptation\nof compact ASR models without the need for\nresource-intensive pre-training.\n\n2. Related Work\n2.1. Speech Representation Learning\nThe current ASR landscape is dominated by frameworks\nsuch as Baevski et al. (2020) and Babu et al. (2022), which\nleverage self-supervised learning for robust feature extraction. While models like Radford et al. (2023) have pushed\nthe boundaries of accuracy via large-scale supervision, their\ncomputational footprint remains prohibitive for edge devices. Consequently, lightweight architectures like Moonshine (Useful Sensors, 2024; King & Sabra, 2025) have\nemerged as essential for local, resource-constrained deployment.\n\n1. Introduction\n\n2.2. Vocabulary Adaptation\n\nRecent advancements in Automatic Speech Recognition\n(ASR) have achieved remarkable performance through largescale, self-supervised learning. However, these models often rely on broad-coverage tokenizers designed for highresource languages, which perform suboptimally on morphologically rich languages like Bengali. This mismatch\nresults in high token fertility, leading to increased sequence\nlength and autoregressive collapse during inference.\n\nTokenization quality is a primary determinant of model\nperformance (Rust et al., 2021). Prior efforts, such as\nWECHSEL (Minixhofer et al., 2022) and FOCUS (Dobler &\nde Melo, 2023), have proposed innovative ways to initialize\nsubword embeddings for cross-lingual transfer. However,\nthese methods primarily address text-based Large Language\nModels (LLMs). Our work extends these principles to ASR\nby identifying ”tokenizer transplantation” as a critical requirement for preventing autoregressive drift in morphologically rich scripts.\n\n1\n\nKhulna University of Engineering & Technology, Bangladesh\nMilitary Institute of Science and Technology, Bangladesh. Correspondence to: Sanjid Hasan <hasan2203090@stud.kuet.ac.bd>.\n2\n\n1\nhttps://github.com/Sanjidh090/moonshin\ne-base-bn\n\nProceedings of the 43 rd International Conference on Machine\nLearning, Seoul, South Korea. PMLR 306, 2026. Copyright 2026\nby the author(s).\n\n1\n\n\fTokenizer Transplantation for Bengali ASR\n\n2.3. Bengali ASR\n\nthe network our pipeline begins by fine-tuning the vanilla\nMoonshine-Base model on the Bengali dataset for 21 epochs.\nThis allows the encoder to adapt its acoustic representations\nto Bengali phonetics. However, while the training loss converges, the decoder fails to produce coherent text due to the\nextreme sequence lengths generated by the native Englishoptimized tokenizer.\n\nThe development of Bengali ASR has been accelerated by\ndatasets like Alam et al. (2022) and Faisal et al. (2023).\nWhile recent works (Tabib et al., 2026) have explored longform ASR and speaker diarization (Bredin et al., 2020),\nthere remains a gap in adapting state-of-the-art decoders\nto these languages. By integrating techniques such as\nTokAlign (Liu et al., 2025) and Trans-Tokenization (Delobelle et al., 2024), we provide a robust, reproducible methodology for language-specific vocabulary adaptation.\n\n4.2. Phase 2: Tokenizer Transplantation\nTo resolve the decoding bottleneck while retaining the newly\nlearned acoustic weights, tokenizer transplantation is performed on the 21-epoch fine-tuned model. The original\ndecoder tokenizer is replaced with the BUET BanglaBERT\nWordPiece tokenizer (Bhattacharjee et al., 2022). Decoder\nembeddings are mathematically resized from the original vocabulary size (Vold ) to the Bengali target vocabulary (Vnew ).\n\n3. Tokenizer Fertility and Decoding Instability\nThe original Moonshine tokenizer was optimized primarily for English text. As a result, Bengali words undergo\naggressive byte-level decomposition during tokenization.\nTokenizer fertility is defined as the ratio of generated tokens\nto the total number of words:\n\nΦ=\n\nTotal Tokens\nTotal Words\n\nSpecial tokens are remapped explicitly to preserve decoder\ncompatibility (e.g., mapping BanglaBERT’s ⟨CLS⟩ →\nBOS and ⟨SEP ⟩ → EOS). The 61.5M parameter encoder\narchitecture remains unchanged, preserving the Bengaliadapted acoustic representations learned during Phase 1.\n\n(1)\n\nwhere lower values indicate more compact tokenization. The baseline tokenizer produces Φbaseline = 9.16.\nIn contrast, the transplanted Bengali tokenizer achieves\nΦtransplant = 1.30.\n\n4.3. Phase 3: Two-Stage Recovery Optimization\nBecause the new decoder embeddings are randomly initialized while the acoustic encoder is already fine-tuned,\nstandard optimization leads to transplant rejection and catastrophic forgetting. To stabilize decoder adaptation, a twostage recovery fine-tuning approach is utilized, as illustrated\nin Figure 1:\n\nThe fertility gap substantially affects autoregressive decoding. Long token chains increase the probability of inferencetime error accumulation (Sennrich et al., 2016). Although\nteacher-forced optimization remains stable, autoregressive\ngeneration becomes increasingly fragile, explaining the observed discrepancy between training loss and inference quality.\n\nStage 1 (High LR Recovery): An aggressive initial learning rate (η = 2 × 10−4 ) is applied using the ScheduleFree\nAdamW optimizer (Defazio et al., 2024). This rapidly aligns\nthe new textual embeddings to the acoustic latent space over\n7 epochs without degrading the robust encoder weights.\n\n4. Methodology\n\nStage 2 (Stabilization): Training is resumed from the\n7-epoch checkpoint with a heavily decayed learning rate\n(η = 2 × 10−5 ) to fine-tune the model for grammatical and\nphonetic accuracy.\n\nTo address the catastrophic decoding drift caused by high\ntokenizer fertility, a novel three-phase adaptation pipeline is\nproposed. Rather than training a model from scratch or replacing the vocabulary before fine-tuning, which often leads\nto catastrophic forgetting, the approach explicitly decouples acoustic representation learning from autoregressive\nlanguage modeling. In this section, the sequential steps of\nthe framework are detailed: initial acoustic adaptation of the\nbase model, surgical transplantation of a native-script vocabulary, and a specialized recovery optimization schedule\ndesigned to stabilize the newly initialized decoder embeddings.\n\nTo maximize memory efficiency, BF16 Automatic Mixed\nPrecision (AMP), gradient checkpointing, and gradient accumulation (step 8) are applied to achieve an effective batch\nsize of 32 throughout both stages.\n\n5. Experimental Setup\nAll model adaptations and recovery fine-tuning schedules were implemented using PyTorch, leveraging a local\nNVIDIA GeForce RTX 4070 hardware accelerator with\n12.9 GB VRAM to support memory-efficient execution via\nAutomatic Mixed Precision (AMP) and gradient checkpointing. Transcript evaluations, Word Error Rate (WER) met-\n\n4.1. Phase 1: Initial Acoustic Fine-Tuning\nRather than replacing the tokenizer prior to any training\nwhich often destroys pretrained alignments and destabilizes\n2\n\n\fTokenizer Transplantation for Bengali ASR\nPhase 1: Acoustic Adaptation & Surgery\n\nPhase 2: Two-Stage Transplant Recovery\n\nTransplanted\nModel\n\n1. Initial Acoustic Fine-Tuning\n\n3. Stage 1: High LR Recovery\n\n• Model: Moonshine-Base (61.5M)\n\n• Base: Transplanted Architecture\n\n• Optim: AdamW (η = 2 × 10−5 )\n\n• Optim: ScheduleFree AdamW (η = 2 × 10−4 )\n\n• Result: 21-Epoch Adapted Encoder\n\n• Result: 7-Epoch Checkpoint\n\nExtract\n21-Ep Encoder\n\n7-Epoch\nCheckpoint\n\nPhase 3: Validation Pipeline\n\n5. Autoregressive Evaluation\n\nEpoch-Level\nEval\n\n• Gen: Beam Search (Width=4, Pen=1.2)\n• Metric: Greedy WER (Random 64 Subset)\n• Target: Save on Best WER (Patience=4)\n\n2. Tokenizer Transplantation\n\n4. Stage 2: Stabilization\n\n• Base: 21-Ep Fine-Tuned Encoder\n\n• Base: 7-Epoch Transplant Checkpoint\n\n• Swap: BanglaBERT Vocabulary Transplant\n\n• Optim: Reduced LR (η = 2 × 10−5 )\n\n• Align: Map ⟨CLS⟩ → BOS, ⟨SEP ⟩ → EOS\n\n• Updates: Dynamic Masking Enabled\n\nFigure 1. Overview of the Tokenizer Transplantation Methodology.\n\nric verification computations, and Real-Time Factor (RTF)\nspeed benchmarking profiles were executed using the cloudhosted Kaggle environment.\n\ndrift observed in the baseline.\n\nTable 1. Tokenizer Fertility Comparison\n\n5.1. Dataset\n\nTokenizer\n\nExperiments utilize the Lipi-Ghor-882 dataset (Hasan et al.,\n2026), an 882-hour multi-speaker Bengali corpus curated\nfrom diverse open-source media. Audio is normalized to\n16kHz mono. Silent segments and non-speech artifacts are\naggressively filtered using Voice Activity Detection (VAD)\nvia Pyannote (Bredin et al., 2020). This builds upon foundational Bengali speech corpora such as OOD-Speech (Faisal\net al., 2023) and Bengali Common Voice (Alam et al., 2022)\nby offering long-form, highly diverse multi-speaker data.\n\nOriginal Moonshine\nTransplanted Bengali (BUET)\n\nFertility (Φ)\n9.16\n1.30\n\n6.2. End-to-End ASR Performance\nTo evaluate the real-world efficacy of the tokenizer transplantation pipeline, the proposed model is compared against\na spectrum of zero-shot and fine-tuned baselines on the 5%\nheld-out Lipi-Ghor test set (comprising 5,931 utterances).\n\n5.2. Evaluation Metrics\nTranscription quality is evaluated using Word Error Rate\n(WER) and Character Error Rate (CER), while inference\nefficiency is measured using Real-Time Factor (RTF). During training, Greedy WER is monitored on a randomized\n64-sample validation subset at the end of each epoch, utilizing beam search (width = 4, repetition penalty = 1.2).\nEarly stopping is triggered based on the best WER, with a\npatience of four epochs.\n\nAs detailed in Table 2, the transplanted Moonshine-Base\narchitecture achieves a highly competitive Word Error Rate\n(WER) of 21.54%, substantially outperforming both the\nZero-Shot Meta MMS 1B and the Fine-Tuned Conformer\nbaselines.\nMost notably, the proposed model achieves a Character\nError Rate (CER) of 10.79%, the lowest among all tested\narchitectures. This indicates that the native-script vocabulary empowers the decoder to construct morphologically\ncomplex Bengali words with higher sub-word accuracy than\nthe byte-fallback approach utilized by Whisper. Furthermore, this accuracy is achieved with an order-of-magnitude\nreduction in parameters, matching the performance of the\n∼769M parameter Faster Whisper Medium model with only\n∼61.5M parameters.\n\n6. Results\n6.1. Mitigation of Autoregressive Collapse\nTokenizer transplantation dramatically reduces Bengali sequence fragmentation (Table 1). By compressing the token\nrepresentations, autoregressive decoding becomes substantially more stable, completely preventing the catastrophic\n\n3\n\n\fTokenizer Transplantation for Bengali ASR\nTable 2. Global ASR Performance Comparison on the Lipi-Ghor Test Set. The proposed transplanted Moonshine model achieves a\ncompetitive WER and the lowest CER while operating with significantly fewer parameters than the Whisper and Conformer baselines.\n\nPre-training Strategy\n\nModel Architecture\n\nParameters\n\nWER (%)\n\nCER (%)\n\nZero-Shot\nZero-Shot\nZero-Shot\nZero-Shot\n\nSeamless M4T-v2\nOpenAI Whisper large-v3\nMeta MMS 1B\nHishab TITU Conformer Large\n\n∼2.3B\n∼1.55B\n∼1B\n∼120M\n\n66.71\n84.53\n43.06\n30.51\n\n45.54\n72.92\n21.16\n18.23\n\nFine-Tuned\nFine-Tuned\n\nConformer Baseline (fast-conformer)\nFaster Whisper Medium (Tustugi)\n\n∼120M\n∼769M\n\n24.67\n21.28\n\n15.56\n11.18\n\nProposed\n\nMoonshine Base (Transplanted Tokenizer)\n\n∼61.5M\n\n21.54\n\n10.79\n\nTable 3. Inference Efficiency on the 22-Hour DL Sprint Benchmark. The proposed model drastically outperforms competition\nbaselines in speed while recovering accuracy.\nModel Architecture\n\nOptimization\n\nTime (22h)\n\nRTF\n\nWhisper-Medium\nHishab-Titu Conformer\nProposed Moonshine-base\nMoonshine-tiny\n\nCTranslate2 / Dual T4\nStandard PyTorch\nTokenizer Transplant\nBaseline (Failed WER)\n\n∼26 min\n∼17 min\n∼7 min\n∼5 min\n\n0.0190\n0.0120\n0.0053\n0.0038\n\n7. Conclusion\nThis study introduced tokenizer transplantation for the Bengali adaptation of the Moonshine ASR model. Analysis\nidentified excessive tokenizer fertility as a primary source\nof autoregressive instability in compact models. By initially fine-tuning the acoustic representations, replacing the\nnative tokenizer with a morphologically aligned Bengali\ntokenizer, and implementing a two-stage recovery training\npipeline, inference stability on the Lipi-Ghor dataset was\nsubstantially improved. These findings demonstrate that\ndecoupling acoustic adaptation from vocabulary alignment\nserves as a critical, underexplored strategy for democratizing lightweight ASR systems in low-resource languages.\n\nFigure 2. Efficiency Frontier. The proposed model (cyan)\nachieves a favorable trade-off between performance and efficiency.\n\n6.3. Inference Efficiency and Edge Viability\nTo contextualize the computational efficiency of the proposed architecture, inference speeds were compared against\ntop-performing baselines evaluated during the DL Sprint 4.0\nBengali ASR competition (Hasan et al., 2026). Benchmarks\nare calculated based on the 22-hour hidden test set utilized\nin the competition.\n\nAcknowledgments\n\nAs demonstrated in Table 3, while standard architectures like\nWhisper-Medium required heavily engineered, parallelized\nCTranslate2 pipelines (Klein et al., 2017) to achieve a RealTime Factor (RTF) of ∼0.019, the proposed MoonshineBase with the transplanted BanglaBERT tokenizer achieves\nan RTF of 0.0053 natively.\n\nThe authors express their sincere gratitude to the Department\nof Computer Science and Engineering (CSE) at Khulna University of Engineering & Technology (KUET) for providing\naccess to the specialized PC environment used to execute\nthe fine-tuning and core adaptation stages of this research.\n\nAlthough the original vanilla Moonshine model processes\nthe 22-hour set in slightly less time (RTF ∼0.0038), it yields\ncatastrophic WERs near 100% (Hasan et al., 2026). Tokenizer transplantation slightly increases sequence processing\ntime due to accurate autoregressive generation, yet successfully salvages the model’s accuracy while remaining 3.5×\nfaster than highly optimized Whisper deployments and 2.2×\nfaster than Conformer architectures.\n\nReferences\nAlam, S. et al. Bengali common voice speech dataset for\nautomatic speech recognition. ResearchGate, 2022.\nBabu, A., Wang, C., Tjandra, A., et al. Xls-r: Selfsupervised cross-lingual speech representation learning\nat scale. In Proceedings of Interspeech, 2022.\n4\n\n\fTokenizer Transplantation for Bengali ASR\n\nBaevski, A., Zhou, H., Mohamed, A., and Auli, M. wav2vec\n2.0: A framework for self-supervised learning of speech\nrepresentations. In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS), 2020.\n\nRust, P., Pfeiffer, J., Vulić, I., Litschko, S., and Glavaš, G.\nHow good is your tokenizer? on the monolingual performance of multilingual language models. In Proceedings\nof the Association for Computational Linguistics (ACL),\n2021.\n\nBhattacharjee, A., Hasan, M. T., Ahmad, W., et al.\nBanglabert: Language model pretraining and evaluating\nunder-resourced language nlp. In Findings of the Association for Computational Linguistics: EMNLP, 2022.\n\nSennrich, R., Haddow, B., and Birch, A. Neural machine\ntranslation of rare words with subword units. In Proceedings of the Association for Computational Linguistics\n(ACL), 2016.\n\nBredin, H., Yin, R., Coria, J. M., et al. pyannote.audio: neural building blocks for speaker diarization. In Proceedings of the IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\nSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2020.\n\nTabib, H. M. S., Rifti, I. A., Ehsan, A. M. A., Dasgupta,\nS., Sowdha, M. Z. M. S., Sarker, A. J., Hasan, M. M.,\nSaha, A., Nobo, M. N. M., Bhattacharjee, S., Bhomik,\nT., Swapnil, A. N., and Kabir, S. Bengali-loop: Community benchmarks for long-form bangla asr and speaker\ndiarization, 2026.\n\nDefazio, A., Mishchenko, K., and Bottou, L. The road\nless scheduled. In Proceedings of the 41st International\nConference on Machine Learning (ICML), 2024.\n\nUseful Sensors. Moonshine: Lightweight speech recognition models. GitHub repository, 2024.\n\nDelobelle, P. et al. Trans-tokenization and cross-lingual vocabulary transfers: Language adaptation of llms for lowresource nlp. arXiv preprint arXiv:2408.04303, 2024.\nDobler, K. and de Melo, G. Focus: Effective embedding\ninitialization for monolingual specialization of multilingual models. In Proceedings of the Empirical Methods in\nNatural Language Processing (EMNLP), 2023.\nFaisal, F. et al. Ood-speech: A large bengali speech recognition dataset for out-of-distribution benchmarking. arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2305.09688, 2023.\nHasan, S. et al. Make it hard to hear, easy to learn: Longform bengali asr and speaker diarization. arXiv preprint\narXiv:2602.23070, 2026.\nKing, J. and Sabra, A. Flavors of moonshine: Tiny specialized asr models for edge devices. arXiv preprint\narXiv:2509.02523, 2025.\nKlein, G., Kim, Y., Deng, Y., Senellart, J., and Rush, A. M.\nOpennmt: Open-source toolkit for neural machine translation, 2017.\nLiu, Y. et al. Tokalign: Efficient vocabulary adaptation via\ntoken alignment. In Proceedings of the Association for\nComputational Linguistics (ACL), 2025.\nMinixhofer, B. et al. Wechsel: Effective initialization of\nsubword embeddings for cross-lingual transfer of monolingual language models. In Proceedings of the North\nAmerican Chapter of the Association for Computational\nLinguistics (NAACL), 2022.\nRadford, A., Kim, J. W., Xu, T., et al. Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision. In Proceedings\nof the International Conference on Machine Learning\n(ICML), 2023.\n5\n\n\f", "numLines": 491, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 491}}}
